WEBVTT

00:00.306 --> 00:03.874
Narrator: On this illuminating
episode of "MythBusters"...

00:03.876 --> 00:05.309
Ah.

00:05.311 --> 00:06.810
There went his first glass.

00:06.812 --> 00:09.268
Narrator:
...Adam and Jamie have a smashing time...

00:09.270 --> 00:12.203
I can see nothing! This is insane!

00:12.205 --> 00:14.998
...as they reflect on
something truly enlightening.

00:15.000 --> 00:17.796
Adam: It looks great. I didn't think
it would be this good.

00:17.798 --> 00:19.827
Narrator:
Can you really use mirrors and the sun...

00:19.829 --> 00:22.933
Behold! I am the master of the sun!

00:22.935 --> 00:25.270
...as a form of ancient lighting?

00:25.272 --> 00:28.078
- There it is. Doink!
- Man, that's bright.

00:28.080 --> 00:30.346
Narrator: Then, Tory, Grant, and Kari...

00:30.348 --> 00:32.951
Grant: - Ha!
Tory: - That was hairball.

00:32.953 --> 00:34.988
...investigate a freeway fable...

00:34.990 --> 00:36.822
Grant: I think there are some
law-enforcement people

00:36.824 --> 00:38.926
who would be very
interested in talking to us.

00:38.928 --> 00:41.929
Narrator: ...that you can slow down
an out-of-control vehicle...

00:41.931 --> 00:44.867
Kari:
Your idea of a safe stop is to shank me?

00:44.869 --> 00:48.172
Narrator:
...by playing bumper cars on the blacktop.

00:48.174 --> 00:50.173
Tory: We're on the road to madness!

00:52.808 --> 00:54.509
Narrator: Who are the MythBusters?

00:55.812 --> 00:57.746
- Adam Savage...
- Whoo!

00:57.748 --> 00:58.981
What more did you need to know?

00:58.983 --> 01:00.249
...and Jamie Hyneman.

01:00.251 --> 01:02.119
When in doubt, C-4.

01:02.121 --> 01:07.125
Between them, more than 30 years
of special-effects experience.

01:07.127 --> 01:09.761
Joining them... Grant Imahara...

01:09.763 --> 01:11.663
It's lethal, people!

01:11.665 --> 01:14.598
- ...Kari Byron...
- Jamie just doesn't look right.

01:14.600 --> 01:17.700
- ...and Tory Belleci.
- And touchdown.

01:17.702 --> 01:19.702
They don't just tell the myths,

01:19.704 --> 01:22.804
they put them to the test.

01:22.806 --> 01:27.806
MythBusters 9x11 - Let There Be Light
Original air date June 22, 2011

01:27.908 --> 01:32.908
Sync and corrected by atrn97g
www.addic7ed.com

01:33.845 --> 01:37.013
- I've got a story for you to reflect on.
- Hit me.

01:37.015 --> 01:39.750
I <i>will</i> hit you... with the sun's rays.

01:39.752 --> 01:41.919
In the film "The Mummy", there's a scene

01:41.921 --> 01:44.554
in which the hero has to
go deep into a dark tomb,

01:44.556 --> 01:45.956
and in order to light his way,

01:45.958 --> 01:49.160
he kicks into gear a system
of ancient Egyptian mirrors

01:49.162 --> 01:52.129
which bounce the sun's rays from outside

01:52.131 --> 01:55.099
deep into the bowels of the cavernous tomb,

01:55.101 --> 01:56.567
so that they can navigate safely.

01:56.569 --> 01:57.734
How enlightened.

01:57.736 --> 01:59.937
Well, that's the question, isn't it?

01:59.939 --> 02:01.405
That's the question.

02:01.407 --> 02:02.639
And here's the clip.

02:02.641 --> 02:05.408
Sunlight is bounced into the mummy's tomb.

02:05.410 --> 02:08.978
"And then there was light".

02:08.979 --> 02:13.748
But is this ancient
illumination really possible?

02:13.750 --> 02:15.416
So, what do you want to do first?

02:15.418 --> 02:18.152
Well, look, this myth is all
about lighting up the darkness

02:18.154 --> 02:19.721
with the sun's rays reflected.

02:19.723 --> 02:21.356
We need to answer the question...

02:21.358 --> 02:23.558
what does it mean to light up the darkness?

02:23.560 --> 02:25.894
We need to define that...
what's the minimum amount

02:25.896 --> 02:28.430
of light necessary to move
around in an unfamiliar space?

02:28.432 --> 02:30.598
Exactly, and I think I've got

02:30.600 --> 02:33.201
just the procedure to test this out.

02:33.203 --> 02:35.770
- Okay...
- Oh, don't worry. You're gonna love it.

02:37.172 --> 02:39.973
Before we start bouncing light
around the shop with mirrors,

02:39.975 --> 02:42.108
we need to determine a couple of benchmarks

02:42.110 --> 02:43.977
that we'll be aiming for in these tests.

02:43.979 --> 02:46.646
The first one we've determined
is the Hollywood benchmark.

02:46.648 --> 02:48.014
This is the amount of lighting

02:48.016 --> 02:49.849
that they used while filming the film

02:49.851 --> 02:52.251
that properly tells the
story of a light beam

02:52.253 --> 02:55.153
bouncing around with
mirrors and lighting up a room.

02:55.155 --> 02:56.921
The second benchmark is what I consider

02:56.923 --> 02:58.690
to be the heart and soul of this story,

02:58.692 --> 03:01.093
and it is, what is the minimum amount

03:01.095 --> 03:04.263
of ambient light required to see?

03:05.532 --> 03:08.100
Narrator:
So, step one is finding the minimum

03:08.102 --> 03:10.336
benchmark light level needed to see by,

03:10.338 --> 03:14.674
and Adam's brain wave to
test it is a makeshift maze.

03:14.676 --> 03:17.444
Adam: We are going to try and make
it through this obstacle course

03:17.446 --> 03:18.712
under very low-light conditions

03:18.714 --> 03:20.480
to determine the minimum light conditions

03:20.482 --> 03:22.115
you can make it through
this obstacle course

03:22.117 --> 03:24.051
without breaking anything.

03:24.053 --> 03:27.288
[ glass shatters, clinking ]

03:27.290 --> 03:28.756
That's the sound of failure.

03:28.758 --> 03:30.458
Narrator: With the course set,

03:30.460 --> 03:32.326
the guys focus on benchmark one...

03:32.328 --> 03:34.228
the Hollywood level of illumination.

03:34.230 --> 03:35.797
Jamie: I'm all set.

03:35.799 --> 03:37.432
That means playing with the light level

03:37.434 --> 03:40.668
until it matches that of the movie...

03:40.670 --> 03:42.036
Jamie: Okay, that works for me.

03:42.038 --> 03:44.439
...and then record the lux level.

03:44.441 --> 03:46.174
We're gonna measure our ambient-light level

03:46.176 --> 03:47.542
using a meter like this one,

03:47.544 --> 03:50.245
which receives light in
through the sensor here

03:50.247 --> 03:52.547
and converts that to an electrical signal.

03:52.549 --> 03:54.582
Now, our computer converts that signal

03:54.584 --> 03:57.318
into what is known as lux.

03:57.320 --> 03:59.887
Narrator:
In the days when candles were king,

03:59.889 --> 04:01.923
scientists determined that one lux

04:01.925 --> 04:05.526
is the amount of illumination
that falls over one square meter

04:05.528 --> 04:08.028
if a candle is set one meter away.

04:08.030 --> 04:09.395
Using this scale,

04:09.397 --> 04:13.833
about 300 lux is the minimum
level needed to read by.

04:13.835 --> 04:17.737
But how many lux is the movie scene?

04:17.738 --> 04:20.440
To find out, it's trial by tweaking

04:20.442 --> 04:24.477
as the MythBusters crank
up the levels bit by bit.

04:24.479 --> 04:26.546
201 lux.

04:26.548 --> 04:28.482
And with a benefit of a jump cut or two...

04:28.484 --> 04:29.850
That ought to do it.

04:29.852 --> 04:31.418
...they soon find the level

04:31.420 --> 04:34.754
they think is a lux
look-alike for "The Mummy".

04:34.756 --> 04:37.691
Adam: This looks great. It
looks just like the movie.

04:37.693 --> 04:41.161
Okay. That gives us an average of 200 lux.

04:41.163 --> 04:43.996
Narrator:
So, that's the Hollywood level sorted.

04:43.998 --> 04:46.231
How will benchmark two compare?

04:46.233 --> 04:48.533
Adam's got a plan.

04:48.535 --> 04:50.302
Since the archaeologists in this myth

04:50.304 --> 04:52.170
went from the bright sun into the tomb,

04:52.172 --> 04:53.472
we're gonna do the same thing.

04:53.474 --> 04:55.240
Here I am in Jamie's electronics room

04:55.242 --> 04:57.542
with two lights simulating the bright sun.

04:57.544 --> 05:00.077
I will then leave the electronics room

05:00.079 --> 05:02.480
and walk down the tunnel of Osiris,

05:02.482 --> 05:06.317
otherwise known as Jamie's
battery-and-wire storage shelf.

05:06.319 --> 05:09.153
I will then enter the main shop
area, which will be pitch-black,

05:09.155 --> 05:11.956
and I'll use this rope to guide myself

05:11.958 --> 05:13.357
out into the middle of the shop.

05:13.359 --> 05:15.259
And when I hit the knot...

05:15.261 --> 05:17.895
I turn and start to walk
the obstacle course.

05:17.897 --> 05:21.533
The question is, what is the
minimum amount of light required

05:21.535 --> 05:23.702
for me to walk this obstacle course...

05:23.704 --> 05:25.770
[ glass shatters ]

05:25.772 --> 05:27.472
...without breaking anything?

05:27.474 --> 05:28.941
It's not gonna be easy.

05:28.943 --> 05:31.877
Narrator: To find out, Adam set
his overhead light source

05:31.879 --> 05:33.980
to its bare-minimum setting.

05:33.982 --> 05:36.849
Okay, Adam. Go ahead and do your thing.

05:36.851 --> 05:38.317
Adam: All right. Here I go.

05:38.319 --> 05:41.654
Jamie monitors progress
on an infrared camera.

05:41.656 --> 05:43.255
Holy crap.

05:43.257 --> 05:44.523
There he is.

05:44.525 --> 05:46.558
I can see nothing. [ glass shatters ]

05:46.560 --> 05:48.160
Narrator: And for those of you

05:48.162 --> 05:50.528
who find the sound of
breaking glass disturbing,

05:50.530 --> 05:53.731
now might be a good time
to switch your set to "mute".

05:53.733 --> 05:55.332
Oh !@#*!

05:55.334 --> 05:57.468
This is... I'm the worst
archaeologist ever!

05:57.470 --> 05:58.536
[ glasses shattering ]

05:58.538 --> 06:01.005
Narrator: It's a bruising encounter,

06:01.007 --> 06:02.941
as Adam...

06:02.943 --> 06:04.309
This is insane!

06:04.311 --> 06:06.979
...stumbles his way through
the wineglass maze.

06:06.981 --> 06:08.748
Here I am. I made it to the end.

06:08.750 --> 06:10.750
And it's clear this light level

06:10.752 --> 06:13.152
is far too low for the human-eye test.

06:13.154 --> 06:16.156
[ laughs ] That was a horror show.

06:16.158 --> 06:19.292
Jamie: You pretty much broke every
glass that was in your path.

06:19.294 --> 06:21.727
Yeah, I think we need to
tune up the lights a little bit.

06:21.729 --> 06:23.195
Let's make it a little brighter

06:23.197 --> 06:24.897
and see if I can't make out
some of these shapes.

06:24.899 --> 06:26.231
Okay.

06:26.233 --> 06:28.335
I'll replace the glasses.

06:29.737 --> 06:31.970
Adam tries a slightly
increased light level...

06:31.972 --> 06:34.506
There we go. One notch up.

06:34.508 --> 06:35.841
...and sets off again.

06:35.843 --> 06:37.677
Okay, Adam. You're good to go.

06:37.679 --> 06:39.212
All right. Here I go.

06:39.214 --> 06:41.247
Man, I cannot... ah.

06:41.249 --> 06:42.616
I can't make out...

06:42.618 --> 06:43.850
[ glass shatters ] Ah.

06:43.852 --> 06:46.119
There went his first glass.

06:46.121 --> 06:47.621
I'm starting to be able to see things.

06:47.623 --> 06:48.722
Oh, my eyes are adjusting.

06:48.724 --> 06:50.558
Yeah, he's doing a lot better, actually.

06:50.560 --> 06:52.060
It's still a blur. Ohh!
[ glass shatters ]

06:52.062 --> 06:53.628
There's number two.

06:53.630 --> 06:54.863
Oh! [ glass shatters ]

06:54.865 --> 06:55.898
Number three...

06:55.900 --> 06:59.033
[ glass shatters ] ...four, five...

06:59.035 --> 07:01.536
Narrator:
And after a disappointing start...

07:01.538 --> 07:02.804
[ glass shatters ] ...seven.

07:02.806 --> 07:06.740
...it soon becomes another
catacomb catastrophe.

07:06.742 --> 07:08.609
So they increase the light level again...

07:08.611 --> 07:10.543
[ glass shatters ]

07:10.545 --> 07:11.478
...and again...

07:11.480 --> 07:12.846
[ glass shatters ]

07:12.848 --> 07:14.347
...and again. [ glass shatters ]

07:14.349 --> 07:18.617
But it's not until light level
six that Adam finally makes it.

07:18.619 --> 07:20.185
This is it. This is the light level.

07:20.187 --> 07:21.620
I'm gonna make it the whole way.

07:21.622 --> 07:24.323
Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh.

07:24.325 --> 07:25.991
Hunh!

07:25.993 --> 07:27.392
I made it.

07:28.662 --> 07:30.362
Narrator: So, they break out the luxmeter

07:30.364 --> 07:33.900
to shed some science on this final setting.

07:34.502 --> 07:36.502
What's the verdict? How dim was it?

07:36.704 --> 07:39.238
I get .389 of a lux.

07:39.240 --> 07:40.739
- Of ambient light?
- Yeah.

07:40.741 --> 07:42.774
That is amazingly dim.

07:42.776 --> 07:47.044
At 0.39 lux, the minimum human-eye level

07:47.046 --> 07:50.815
is 500 times dimmer than Hollywood.

07:50.817 --> 07:53.651
And with both benchmarks in the bag,

07:53.653 --> 07:55.719
the question now is,

07:55.721 --> 07:59.623
can bouncing light with mirrors
beat either benchmark?

07:59.625 --> 08:01.759
All right. Let's turn out the lights.
[ fingers snap ]

