08:11.803 --> 08:13.104
All right, so, this next myth

08:13.106 --> 08:15.974
is all about driving fast, out of control,

08:15.976 --> 08:17.575
and it's totally dangerous.

08:17.577 --> 08:19.077
I love it already. What is it?

08:19.079 --> 08:20.812
Could you... if a car was out of control,

08:20.814 --> 08:23.314
could you overtake them,
get in front of them,

08:23.316 --> 08:24.682
and then slow down

08:24.684 --> 08:26.918
till you brought that
out-of-control car to a stop?

08:26.920 --> 08:30.054
So, as if they had fallen
asleep or had a heart attack.

08:30.056 --> 08:31.956
- Exactly.
- Great. Let's try it.

08:31.958 --> 08:34.357
Narrator:
When a driver passes out at the wheel,

08:34.360 --> 08:37.294
things get very bad very fast,

08:37.296 --> 08:39.730
but does it have to end up like this?

08:39.732 --> 08:41.097
[ tires screech, crash ]

08:41.100 --> 08:44.034
Well, apparently not, because
according to this myth,

08:44.035 --> 08:47.837
you can safely stop a runaway
car by overtaking it,

08:47.974 --> 08:50.708
then carefully bringing it to a standstill.

08:50.710 --> 08:53.611
Freeway fact or blacktop baloney?

08:53.613 --> 08:55.813
Okay, as I see it, we have two scenarios.

08:55.815 --> 08:58.417
First, the driver has lost
total control of the car

08:58.419 --> 09:00.619
and has no influence over it at all.

09:00.621 --> 09:03.389
There's no steering, and
the foot is off the accelerator.

09:03.391 --> 09:04.857
So just coasting, then.

09:04.859 --> 09:06.091
Exactly.

09:06.093 --> 09:08.360
The second scenario
is a little more extreme.

09:08.362 --> 09:09.996
There's still no steering,

09:09.998 --> 09:12.298
but the foot's jammed
onto the accelerator.

09:12.300 --> 09:13.499
Would <i>that</i> make a difference?

09:13.501 --> 09:15.068
All right, so we have two tests.

09:15.070 --> 09:17.403
It sounds like we need to
go to stunt-driving school.

09:17.405 --> 09:19.606
I mean, if this myth is
about a car out of control,

09:19.608 --> 09:21.141
we need to see what it feels like

09:21.143 --> 09:22.842
to be in a car that's out of control.

09:22.844 --> 09:24.711
That is a fantastic idea.

09:24.713 --> 09:27.547
Narrator: Cue our ramped-up shot,
and they're ready to roll.

09:27.549 --> 09:29.282
We're out at the Alameda runway.

09:29.284 --> 09:31.317
But before we can start our experiment,

09:31.319 --> 09:33.587
we need to learn a
little precision driving.

09:33.589 --> 09:35.689
We're gonna learn how to approach, bump,

09:35.691 --> 09:37.157
and overtake a car.

09:37.159 --> 09:40.795
Yep, and the man to take
charge of all that scary stuff...

09:40.797 --> 09:43.698
longtime driving instructor Marvin Ruff.

09:43.700 --> 09:46.168
What sorts of skills would we need to learn

09:46.170 --> 09:48.470
in order to pull this maneuver off?

09:48.472 --> 09:50.573
You need to learn how to approach a car,

09:50.575 --> 09:52.008
how to get alongside it,

09:52.010 --> 09:54.377
and how to slowly make
contact with that car

09:54.379 --> 09:55.478
and get it to stop.

09:57.380 --> 10:00.382
Unlike the real testing to come later,

10:00.384 --> 10:01.683
for <i>this</i> training,

10:01.685 --> 10:04.319
Kari will always be in control of her car,

10:04.321 --> 10:06.921
and Marvin's part is to teach Grant to...

10:06.923 --> 10:08.556
20 miles an hour?

10:08.558 --> 10:09.957
...overtake...

10:11.326 --> 10:12.726
Okay. Move over in front.

10:12.728 --> 10:14.194
Grant: Okay. Here we go.

10:14.196 --> 10:15.696
...slow his car down...

10:15.698 --> 10:17.431
Kari: Oh, my God. This feels crazy.

10:17.433 --> 10:19.300
...back the bumper against hers...

10:19.302 --> 10:21.102
Ruff: Like landing an airplane.

10:21.104 --> 10:23.572
Tory: He's slowing down too
fast! We're gonna crash!

10:25.008 --> 10:26.208
Ohh!

10:26.210 --> 10:27.809
You are good.

10:27.811 --> 10:30.012
Now just start pushing on that brake.

10:30.014 --> 10:31.948
...and bring it all to a stop.

10:31.950 --> 10:33.416
[ tires screech ]

10:33.418 --> 10:35.285
- Okay. There it is.
- Nice.

10:35.287 --> 10:36.986
[ laughs ]

10:36.988 --> 10:39.255
Thank you. That's awesome.

10:39.257 --> 10:41.090
Tory: Yeah, we didn't die!

10:41.092 --> 10:45.827
So, that's training hurdle one
passed with flying colors.

10:45.829 --> 10:47.795
[ tires screech ]

10:47.797 --> 10:49.396
All right. What do you think?

10:49.398 --> 10:51.098
Eh, well, we were only going 20,

10:51.100 --> 10:53.066
but I think you did a really nice job.

10:53.068 --> 10:55.802
Grant: I only did that at 20 miles an hour.

10:55.804 --> 10:57.938
I think as we attempt to try this

10:57.940 --> 11:01.542
at faster and faster speeds,
it's gonna get a lot harder.

11:01.544 --> 11:03.544
Narrator: Next, it's challenge two...

11:03.546 --> 11:06.714
learning what it feels like
when something goes wrong,

11:06.716 --> 11:10.085
courtesy of the infamous pit maneuver.

11:10.087 --> 11:13.489
Tory: Here we go, in three, two, one, go.

11:13.491 --> 11:15.624
Trying to get away from the law.

11:15.626 --> 11:18.260
Narrator: Scarier still, the rain set in.

11:18.262 --> 11:20.529
And ready to put them into a spin,

11:20.531 --> 11:23.131
Marvin stalks the red car...

11:23.133 --> 11:25.534
Grant: Here he comes! This is it!

11:25.536 --> 11:27.002
Narrator: ...pulls up alongside...

11:27.004 --> 11:29.370
Tory: Get ready to go out of control!

11:30.372 --> 11:32.206
...touches the rear fender...

11:32.208 --> 11:33.941
Grant: Whoa!

11:33.943 --> 11:35.342
...and...

11:35.344 --> 11:36.677
[ tires screech ]

11:36.679 --> 11:38.412
Whoa! Whoa!

11:38.414 --> 11:39.613
Whoo!

11:39.615 --> 11:42.183
Tory: We just got pit-maneuvered!

11:42.185 --> 11:44.085
[ tires screech ]

11:45.287 --> 11:47.390
That felt so good! [ laughs ]

11:47.392 --> 11:49.992
It's good to be out of control sometimes.

11:49.994 --> 11:53.597
Narrator:
Training's done. They're bumped, pumped...

11:53.599 --> 11:55.799
Tory: We just got pit-maneuvered!

11:55.801 --> 11:57.768
...and amped to ramp.

11:57.770 --> 12:01.238
I think I feel the need,
the need for speed.

12:01.240 --> 12:03.274
I think we can go faster now.

12:03.276 --> 12:04.909
Narrator: Coming up on "MythBusters"...

12:04.911 --> 12:07.011
♪ Ta-da! ♪

12:07.013 --> 12:11.249
Narrator: ...then, techniques of
bumper-stopping a careering car.

12:12.652 --> 12:15.154
Tory: Here we go. Oh.

12:15.156 --> 12:17.256
Ruff: All right! Nice work!

12:25.496 --> 12:30.933
Narrator: Can mirrors illuminate a murky
mausoleum using the sun?

12:30.935 --> 12:33.169
The film "The Mummy" claims it can.

12:33.171 --> 12:35.905
"And then there was light".

12:35.907 --> 12:39.007
But is this history or hooey?

12:39.009 --> 12:40.876
To find out, Adam and Jamie

12:40.878 --> 12:43.645
have established two
benchmarks of illumination...

12:43.647 --> 12:44.747
[ glass shatters ]

12:44.749 --> 12:46.349
Adam: I can see nothing!

12:46.351 --> 12:48.784
- ...a Hollywood lighting level...
Jamie: - 200 lux.

12:48.786 --> 12:50.753
...and a human-eye level.

12:50.755 --> 12:52.889
I get .389 of a lux.

12:52.891 --> 12:55.959
And now, by using two types of mirrors,

12:55.961 --> 13:00.063
will they be able to
match either benchmark?

13:00.065 --> 13:04.234
Well, first up, Adam polishes up
some ye olde metal mirrors,

13:04.236 --> 13:06.804
and Jamie lines them up.

13:06.806 --> 13:08.472
Jamie:
We've set these mirrors up to bounce light

13:08.474 --> 13:11.308
from mirror to mirror down
the length of the room.

13:11.310 --> 13:13.344
Now, our goal is to see if those beams

13:13.346 --> 13:15.112
will raise the ambient-light level.

13:15.714 --> 13:17.482
Narrator: To test this myth,

13:17.484 --> 13:19.851
they'll line up their mirrors
and try a sun substitute.

13:19.853 --> 13:23.755
The artificial sun for this test
needs to be like the sun...

13:23.757 --> 13:25.757
that is, heavily collimated.

13:25.759 --> 13:27.225
That means all the light beams

13:27.227 --> 13:29.528
are actually traveling
parallel to each other,

13:29.530 --> 13:32.064
and the most collimated
light we can rent is this...

13:32.066 --> 13:33.966
a spotlight.

13:33.968 --> 13:35.634
♪ Ta-da! ♪

13:35.636 --> 13:37.603
Narrator:
And with the metal mirrors lined up,

13:37.605 --> 13:39.805
it's time for a moment of discovery.

13:39.807 --> 13:41.406
When the shop lights are turned off,

13:41.408 --> 13:44.643
how bright will the mirrors' light be?

13:44.645 --> 13:47.045
All right. Let's turn out the lights.
[ fingers snap ]

13:47.047 --> 13:51.016
It looks great. I didn't think
it would be this good.

13:51.018 --> 13:52.451
Narrator: Adam's right.

13:52.453 --> 13:55.654
First impressions are that
these mirrors are working well.

13:55.656 --> 13:58.123
But, crucially, how are they
doing in the lux department?

13:58.125 --> 14:00.692
- Got it?
Adam: - All right.

14:00.694 --> 14:03.562
The average ambient light
of the polished metal...

14:03.564 --> 14:06.031
1.13 lux.

14:06.033 --> 14:08.867
Do our light-bouncing mirrors
work like they do in the film?

14:08.869 --> 14:10.336
I'd say that they do.

14:10.338 --> 14:13.205
There is an impressive amount
of ambient light in this room

14:13.207 --> 14:15.074
solely because of the mirrors.

14:15.076 --> 14:16.976
Do they <i>look</i> like they do in the movie?

14:16.978 --> 14:19.278
No, they do not.

14:19.280 --> 14:21.347
By the six mirror, this beam
is no longer collimated.

14:21.349 --> 14:24.017
It is a heavily, heavily scattered affair.

14:24.019 --> 14:26.552
Narrator: The scattering, or loss of focus,

14:26.554 --> 14:27.787
is not a good look,

14:27.789 --> 14:30.790
but the level of light itself is promising.

14:30.792 --> 14:33.125
It's clearly not as bright as the movie,

14:33.127 --> 14:36.461
but it is better than their
naked-eye benchmark.

14:36.463 --> 14:39.530
So, can modern glass be a
more polished performer?

14:40.932 --> 14:42.700
This is our polished metal mirror...

14:42.702 --> 14:44.802
and this is our glass mirror.

14:44.804 --> 14:47.605
Obviously, the glass mirror
is more reflective,

14:47.607 --> 14:49.674
but is that what we really want?

14:49.676 --> 14:52.511
It may be the case that the metal mirror

14:52.513 --> 14:54.546
is actually diffusing the light more

14:54.548 --> 14:56.949
and therefore lighting up the ambient light

14:56.951 --> 14:58.417
in the room more.

14:58.419 --> 15:00.186
We're just gonna have
to try it to find out.

15:00.188 --> 15:02.754
Narrator:
So, to do that, they position the mirrors

15:02.756 --> 15:05.423
with the overhead lights on, and then...

15:05.425 --> 15:07.625
Adam: Well, the mirrors are
in place. They look great.

15:07.627 --> 15:10.394
Here we go.

15:10.396 --> 15:13.297
[ laughs ] That looks fantastic.

15:13.299 --> 15:14.565
It looks just like the movie.

15:14.567 --> 15:16.200
Surprise, surprise.

15:16.202 --> 15:17.934
The modern glass <i>looks</i> better...

15:17.936 --> 15:19.402
All right. Good.

15:19.404 --> 15:21.471
...but does the data back that up?

15:21.473 --> 15:23.140
Jamie: How did our glass mirrors do?

15:23.142 --> 15:24.675
You're gonna love this.

15:24.677 --> 15:26.443
First, you remember
the ambient-light reading

15:26.445 --> 15:28.713
that we got from the
polished metal was 1.13 lux?

15:28.715 --> 15:29.914
Yeah.

15:29.916 --> 15:34.152
Our glass mirrors came in at .487 lux.

15:34.154 --> 15:36.322
[ laughs ] - Who knew?
- I know.

15:36.324 --> 15:38.224
Less than half. Isn't that amazing?

15:38.226 --> 15:41.294
Jamie: There seems to be more going
on here than meets the eye.

15:41.296 --> 15:42.495
The goal of all this

15:42.497 --> 15:45.164
is to raise the ambient-light
level in a room,

15:45.166 --> 15:47.733
and mirrors alone aren't gonna cut it.

15:47.735 --> 15:50.702
That light needs to hit
something that scatters it.

15:50.704 --> 15:53.871
It could be my white
shirt, or it can be fog,

15:53.873 --> 15:56.707
but it has to scatter to light the room.

15:56.709 --> 15:59.376
Narrator: Because the modern mirrors
give a cleaner beam,

15:59.378 --> 16:01.178
the ambient light they give off

16:01.180 --> 16:03.947
is actually less than the polished metal,

16:03.949 --> 16:05.649
meaning the metal wins.

16:05.651 --> 16:07.117
But what's also clear

16:07.119 --> 16:10.154
is that the real loser in
this proof-of-concept test

16:10.156 --> 16:11.523
is Hollywood.

16:11.525 --> 16:13.525
Look, on this show, we've always known

16:13.527 --> 16:15.594
that Hollywood has a
penchant for exaggeration.

16:15.596 --> 16:18.364
Our Hollywood lighting setup in this shop

16:18.366 --> 16:21.534
was 100 times brighter
than the ambient-light levels

16:21.536 --> 16:23.369
we got in our small-scale testing.

16:23.371 --> 16:25.472
But that doesn't mean this myth is busted.

16:25.474 --> 16:26.506
No, no, no, no.

16:26.508 --> 16:28.474
Because those ambient-light levels

16:28.476 --> 16:30.043
were still 2.5 times brighter

16:30.045 --> 16:31.911
than what we determined was necessary

16:31.913 --> 16:34.313
to safely maneuver through our "tomb".

16:34.315 --> 16:36.515
That tells me we have every reason

16:36.517 --> 16:39.218
to go full-scale and bring in the real sun.

16:43.322 --> 16:44.689
Tory: Now that we've trained,

16:44.691 --> 16:46.925
it's time to move on to testing the myth.

16:46.927 --> 16:49.293
The first scenario... it's as if
somebody has been driving,

16:49.295 --> 16:50.461
has passed out at the wheel,

16:50.463 --> 16:53.030
and now they're coasting at high speed.

16:53.032 --> 16:55.032
The speed we're gonna
start at for this first test...

16:55.034 --> 16:56.667
35 miles an hour.

16:56.669 --> 16:58.068
This is gonna be interesting.

16:58.070 --> 17:01.438
Narrator: This time, they're going
to try one big change.

17:01.440 --> 17:03.139
Once Grant gets in front of us,

17:03.141 --> 17:05.441
I'm going to take my hands off the wheel

17:05.443 --> 17:07.477
and my foot off the accelerator

17:07.479 --> 17:09.979
as if I've just passed out.

17:09.981 --> 17:11.446
[ tires screech ]

17:11.449 --> 17:13.550
Let's just hope Grant was paying attention

17:13.551 --> 17:16.586
during his training session.

17:19.957 --> 17:21.925
I don't think he was.

17:21.926 --> 17:23.425
Narrator: And for test one,

17:23.428 --> 17:26.329
gentlemen and lady, start your engines.

17:26.330 --> 17:29.399
Tory: All right, this is 35 mile an hour,

17:29.401 --> 17:31.235
driver's passed out.

17:31.237 --> 17:35.173
Here we go, in three, two, one, go.

17:35.175 --> 17:36.241
[ tires screech ]

17:41.847 --> 17:44.382
All right. We are at 35 miles an hour.

17:44.384 --> 17:46.250
And commence passing out.

17:46.252 --> 17:49.520
Narrator:
Look, mom... no hands and no feet...

17:49.522 --> 17:52.790
making this officially an
out-of-control vehicle...

17:52.792 --> 17:53.958
Tory: Here we go.

17:53.960 --> 17:55.159
...which is Grant's cue

17:55.161 --> 17:57.929
to first nose his way in front...

17:57.931 --> 17:58.996
Ohh!

17:58.998 --> 18:01.098
...before slowing down.

18:02.234 --> 18:06.037
And it's easy-peasy, brakes-a-squeezy,

18:06.039 --> 18:08.272
as he manages to haul Kari in.

18:08.274 --> 18:09.841
Kari: And stop.

18:09.843 --> 18:10.942
[ Grant laughs ]

18:11.944 --> 18:13.445
You did it. You stopped us.

18:13.447 --> 18:15.981
That was a little rough, but it worked.

18:15.983 --> 18:19.084
It totally worked, at
35 miles an hour, too.

18:19.086 --> 18:21.187
- All right. What's next?
- Faster.

18:21.189 --> 18:23.188
All right, let's take it
up to 55 miles an hour,

18:23.190 --> 18:24.657
freeway speed.

18:24.659 --> 18:26.058
Let me point this out.

18:26.060 --> 18:28.427
The bumper of the out-of-control car

18:28.429 --> 18:32.265
is actually underneath the
bumper of the rescue car,

18:32.267 --> 18:34.468
and what that does is
it starts to compromise

18:34.470 --> 18:36.170
the stability of the rescue car,

18:36.172 --> 18:38.873
making it even harder to rescue the person.

18:38.875 --> 18:43.276
Narrator: The 35-mile-an-hour,
no-hands test is down.

18:43.278 --> 18:47.046
Now they're about to up the
danger to freeway speed.

18:47.048 --> 18:48.481
Kari: For this next test,

18:48.483 --> 18:50.383
there's gonna be a little
more jeopardy here,

18:50.385 --> 18:52.785
because that all is great as
long as you're going straight.

18:52.787 --> 18:54.787
We're gonna be passed out at the wheel.

18:54.789 --> 18:57.456
The alignment's not amazing
on this salvaged vehicle,

18:57.458 --> 18:59.358
and we're going double the speed.

18:59.360 --> 19:02.495
Tory: Here we go, in three, two, one, go.

19:02.497 --> 19:05.131
Narrator:
55... plus different-height bumpers...

19:05.133 --> 19:06.967
plus dodgy alignment.

19:06.969 --> 19:09.302
Oh, and no hands, either.

19:09.304 --> 19:10.504
30 miles an hour.

19:13.175 --> 19:15.610
55 miles an hour.

19:15.612 --> 19:17.779
This is too exciting to pass out.

19:17.781 --> 19:19.047
But here we go.

19:19.049 --> 19:21.417
Kari: - This is actually kind of scary.
- I know.

19:21.419 --> 19:22.985
All right. We're passing out.

19:22.987 --> 19:24.320
Hand is off of the wheel.

19:24.322 --> 19:26.955
With Kari comatose behind the wheel,

19:26.957 --> 19:28.824
Grant brakes in front.

19:28.826 --> 19:31.360
If he's a whisker off dead center,

19:31.362 --> 19:33.662
one car or other could spin out.

19:33.664 --> 19:36.098
It's a totally tricky maneuver.

19:36.100 --> 19:37.566
Here we go. Oh.

19:40.637 --> 19:43.138
Ruff: All right! Nice work!

19:43.140 --> 19:45.173
Grant: Whoo-hoo-hoo-hoo!

19:45.175 --> 19:49.245
Uh, that was a little scary, got to say.

19:49.247 --> 19:51.180
It's a lot more challenging,

19:51.182 --> 19:53.482
and at 20 miles an hour,

19:53.484 --> 19:55.718
the corrections are sort of gentle.

19:55.720 --> 19:58.621
At 55, the corrections
have to be a lot faster,

19:58.623 --> 20:01.090
and so it's hard to do it really smooth.

20:01.092 --> 20:04.260
But it worked. We're alive!

20:04.262 --> 20:05.928
It worked at 55 miles an hour.

20:05.930 --> 20:09.031
And, look, our hood is almost
underneath your bumper,

20:09.033 --> 20:10.333
and we didn't lose control.

20:10.335 --> 20:12.502
Narrator: But having survived at 55,

20:12.504 --> 20:15.071
can they let it rest at that?

20:15.073 --> 20:16.839
What if the accelerator were stuck...

20:16.841 --> 20:19.642
Yeah, like, if the guy passes out
and his foot's stuck on the gas.

20:19.644 --> 20:21.577
...Or there was some sort of malfunction?

20:21.579 --> 20:24.680
I like it. Add more danger
to this experiment.

20:24.682 --> 20:27.183
All right. Let's do it.

20:31.959 --> 20:34.227
Narrator:
Adam and Jamie have been reflecting

20:34.229 --> 20:36.730
on some proof-of-concept tests at the shop.

20:36.732 --> 20:39.866
The average ambient light
of the polished metal...

20:39.868 --> 20:42.002
1.13 lux.

20:42.004 --> 20:44.404
Can you really use mirrors
to turn dark into day?

20:44.406 --> 20:46.306
Adam: This is more than enough light

20:46.308 --> 20:48.175
for me to make it through that maze.

20:48.177 --> 20:51.179
Narrator:
It's certainly a case of "so far, so good".

20:51.181 --> 20:53.414
But will these results scale up?

20:53.416 --> 20:56.918
Will using the real sun
and a much larger crypt

20:56.920 --> 20:59.287
be the making of this myth?

20:59.289 --> 21:00.922
Well, this is the place.

21:00.924 --> 21:02.190
Looks great.

21:02.192 --> 21:04.025
Okay, it's not ancient Egypt...

21:04.027 --> 21:06.026
[ laughs ] Shall I open it up?

21:06.028 --> 21:07.261
Absolutely.

21:07.263 --> 21:10.330
...but Treasure Island in San Francisco Bay

21:10.332 --> 21:14.535
uncovers an unexpected
underground treasure.

21:14.537 --> 21:16.303
Well, shall we set up?

21:16.305 --> 21:18.038
Let's turn on the house lights.

21:18.040 --> 21:19.541
All right. House lights up.

21:20.643 --> 21:22.043
Well, this is our space.

21:22.045 --> 21:23.545
Now, it's not a tomb,

21:23.547 --> 21:26.214
but it is underground,
and it's very, very dark,

21:26.216 --> 21:28.584
so it'll be perfect for our testing.

21:29.720 --> 21:33.756
Narrator: Jamie blocks out a few spots
to make total darkness.

21:33.758 --> 21:35.024
Jamie: There we go.

21:35.960 --> 21:37.594
Narrator: Meanwhile, Adam's manufacturing

21:37.596 --> 21:39.596
modern glass mirrors.

21:39.598 --> 21:42.598
Now, I'll wager you're probably
yelling at the screen right now,

21:42.600 --> 21:45.168
wondering why I am building
these with glass mirrors

21:45.170 --> 21:46.669
when our polished metal mirrors

21:46.671 --> 21:49.071
actually gave us a higher
ambient-light reading.

21:49.073 --> 21:51.373
1.13 lux.

21:51.375 --> 21:53.108
This is probably easiest to explain

21:53.110 --> 21:54.843
if you take a look at these two shots

21:54.845 --> 21:56.678
our cameramen filmed this morning.

21:56.680 --> 21:58.647
On the left are the polished metal mirrors.

21:58.649 --> 22:00.015
On the right, the glass.

22:00.017 --> 22:02.218
Now, see how the light from
the polished metal mirrors

22:02.220 --> 22:03.553
peters out really fast?

22:03.555 --> 22:05.422
Compare that to the glass mirrors,

22:05.424 --> 22:06.757
where the light is strong

22:06.759 --> 22:08.592
virtually all the way to the end,

22:08.594 --> 22:10.894
and that's what's really important.

22:10.896 --> 22:13.464
This myth isn't about the
type of mirror you use.

22:13.466 --> 22:15.433
It's about bouncing a beam of light,

22:15.435 --> 22:17.601
and the polished metal
didn't give us that beam.

22:17.603 --> 22:20.271
It only lasted about 15 feet
before it was diffused.

22:20.273 --> 22:22.640
That's why the glass is what we're using

22:22.642 --> 22:25.577
in our full-size tomb.

22:25.579 --> 22:27.411
Narrator: And with that cleared up,

22:27.413 --> 22:30.882
there's just one more
ingredient left... the sun.

22:30.884 --> 22:32.117
Jamie: Now all we need to do

22:32.119 --> 22:34.386
is see if the sun's gonna
cooperate with us,

22:34.388 --> 22:36.388
and that's actually a pretty big if,

22:36.390 --> 22:38.690
because not only do we have to worry

22:38.692 --> 22:41.359
about whether we can reflect
sun into the building...

22:41.361 --> 22:44.597
in other words, is it lined up
at a decent angle for that?...

22:44.599 --> 22:46.532
but also, this is San Francisco,

22:46.534 --> 22:48.935
and it's regularly kind of foggy here.

22:48.937 --> 22:51.271
If we have a few too many clouds,

22:51.273 --> 22:52.606
we're gonna be out of business.

22:52.608 --> 22:55.142
Narrator:
Yep, without the big guy in the sky,

22:55.144 --> 22:57.177
the tomb's doomed.

22:57.179 --> 23:02.749
Well, I can see the sun,
but it is awfully overcast.

23:02.751 --> 23:05.518
It is what it is.

23:05.520 --> 23:07.754
Narrator:
So, with San Francisco's fickle weather

23:07.756 --> 23:10.723
doing its darndest to delay things,

23:10.725 --> 23:12.725
Adam has a backup plan.

23:12.727 --> 23:14.626
Adam: Have you met my sun?

23:14.628 --> 23:17.529
It is a 7,000-watt xenon spotlight.

23:17.531 --> 23:19.064
I'm gonna turn it on now.

23:20.266 --> 23:22.634
Ohh!

23:22.636 --> 23:24.937
Look at that puppy.

23:24.939 --> 23:26.972
Boom!

23:26.974 --> 23:30.109
Behold! I am the master of the sun!

23:30.111 --> 23:31.777
[ laughs evilly ]

23:31.779 --> 23:33.245
Narrator: Adam's humongous light source

23:33.247 --> 23:37.283
gives a whopping 160,000 lux at 50 feet.

23:37.285 --> 23:39.385
[ Adam laughs ]

23:39.387 --> 23:41.887
That is freaking awesome.

23:41.889 --> 23:43.289
Narrator: But will it be bright enough

23:43.291 --> 23:45.458
to illuminate their colossal crypt?

23:45.460 --> 23:46.559
Adam: I think that's right.

23:46.561 --> 23:47.894
Narrator: To find out,

23:47.896 --> 23:49.596
the guys will shine in Adam's sun,

23:49.598 --> 23:52.900
position the mirrors, and
then check the light reading,

23:52.902 --> 23:55.535
starting now.

23:55.537 --> 23:57.237
House lights out.

23:58.439 --> 24:00.073
Shall we bring in the sun?

24:00.075 --> 24:01.907
Sure. Why not?

24:01.909 --> 24:03.309
Let's bring in the first sunbeam.

24:05.645 --> 24:07.079
All right. You ready for it?

24:07.081 --> 24:08.613
I'm ready for it. Bring it on.

24:08.615 --> 24:10.215
Okay, here it comes.

24:10.217 --> 24:12.284
There it is.

24:12.286 --> 24:14.920
Narrator: Just like the movie,
they're using six mirrors,

24:14.922 --> 24:18.590
all of which are around 35 feet apart.

24:18.592 --> 24:20.292
Doink! Man, that's bright.

24:20.294 --> 24:23.529
Dude, that is, like, a two-foot laser beam.

24:23.531 --> 24:25.364
Going for mirror number four.

24:26.800 --> 24:27.867
Nice.

24:27.869 --> 24:29.135
All right. There it is.

24:29.137 --> 24:31.605
That's as good as it gets.

24:31.607 --> 24:33.340
Going for the last mirror.

24:33.342 --> 24:35.608
Okay. Coming down.

24:35.610 --> 24:36.576
Zoop!

24:36.578 --> 24:39.646
That's it. You're in.

24:39.648 --> 24:41.681
♪ Ta-da! ♪

24:41.683 --> 24:44.016
And there we go.

24:44.018 --> 24:45.851
That works pretty good.

24:45.853 --> 24:47.286
I swear, I'm gonna go out on a limb

24:47.288 --> 24:49.221
and say this room is nicely lit.

24:49.223 --> 24:52.924
I can move through the antiques
without hurting anything.

24:52.926 --> 24:54.259
Easily.

24:54.261 --> 24:56.594
Look, nobody can say that
we didn't accurately match

24:56.596 --> 24:59.231
the look and behavior of
this technique in the film.

24:59.233 --> 25:01.400
Yep. It looks just like the tomb.

25:01.402 --> 25:03.002
Narrator: It's a good start,

25:03.004 --> 25:05.838
but what does the all-important data say?

25:05.840 --> 25:07.273
All right. Let's take a reading.

25:09.110 --> 25:10.110
Okay, I got it.

25:10.112 --> 25:11.378
Well, it turns out

25:11.380 --> 25:12.914
that bigger is absolutely better.

25:12.916 --> 25:14.482
Going full-scale with our mirrors

25:14.484 --> 25:16.451
is yielding an ambient-light
reading in this room

25:16.453 --> 25:19.020
of 2.3 lux.

25:19.022 --> 25:20.455
And when you're in this room,

25:20.457 --> 25:22.491
you can totally carefully make
your way among the artifacts

25:22.493 --> 25:24.159
without any difficulty at all.

25:24.161 --> 25:26.795
By both an objective
and an empirical standard,

25:26.797 --> 25:31.199
the theory behind this
technique is totally sound.

25:31.201 --> 25:33.736
Narrator:
In fact, it's over five times brighter

25:33.738 --> 25:36.105
than the minimum level
they determined earlier,

25:36.107 --> 25:38.207
and that's very good news for the myth...

25:38.209 --> 25:40.778
except for one little thing.

25:41.580 --> 25:44.447
Jamie: Going full-scale and using
an artificial light source,

25:44.449 --> 25:46.249
we were able to very closely replicate

25:46.251 --> 25:48.018
what we saw in the movie.

25:48.020 --> 25:50.755
But this story is about using the sun.

25:53.292 --> 25:54.692
Narrator: Jamie's right,

25:54.694 --> 25:58.630
but luckily, the long-lost
sun's finally put in a show,

25:58.632 --> 26:01.332
so let there be light.

26:01.334 --> 26:03.334
The question is, will it be enough light

26:03.336 --> 26:06.970
for an archaeologist such
as me or Mr. Hyneman

26:06.972 --> 26:10.073
to be able to move through a
tomb without breaking anything?

26:10.075 --> 26:11.275
Narrator: Coming right up,

26:11.277 --> 26:14.377
it's runway runaway motor mayhem.

26:14.379 --> 26:15.945
Grant: Ohh! Yeah!

26:20.172 --> 26:24.509
Narrator: Can you really bring an
out-of-control car to a stop

26:24.511 --> 26:27.344
with a dangerous game of bumper cars?

26:27.346 --> 26:28.712
- So far, so good.
- Yeah.

26:28.714 --> 26:30.881
It turns out, you <i>can</i>
slow down a coasting car

26:30.883 --> 26:32.049
using this technique.

26:32.051 --> 26:33.951
But now, I think it's time
to ramp things up.

26:33.953 --> 26:36.287
...By seeing what happens when the driver

26:36.289 --> 26:38.356
has their foot jammed on the accelerator.

26:38.358 --> 26:40.524
This is gonna be a
whole another experience,

26:40.526 --> 26:42.260
because now that the accelerator's stuck,

26:42.262 --> 26:43.661
this car's not gonna want to stop.

26:43.663 --> 26:45.596
Narrator: So, back at Alameda runway,

26:45.598 --> 26:48.200
it's pedal to the metal, literally.

26:48.202 --> 26:50.668
And for that, Tory's going green,

26:50.670 --> 26:53.839
because this time, he's doing the rescuing.

26:53.841 --> 26:55.674
Tory:
All right. Time to go save some lives.

26:55.676 --> 26:57.109
I hope they don't wreck my paint job.

26:57.111 --> 27:00.613
Narrator: This time, he's going
for highway high speed.

27:00.615 --> 27:03.550
For this next test, what
I'm being asked to do

27:03.552 --> 27:06.553
is to depress the
accelerator as if it is stuck

27:06.555 --> 27:08.621
and then take my hands off the wheel.

27:08.623 --> 27:11.858
At no time should I take my
foot off the accelerator.

27:11.860 --> 27:14.493
Totally counter-intuitive
and kind of scary.

27:16.196 --> 27:17.530
We're about to stop a car

27:17.532 --> 27:20.065
going 75 miles an hour out of control

27:20.067 --> 27:22.334
with another car.

27:22.336 --> 27:24.870
Buckle up. It's about to get real.

27:24.872 --> 27:27.339
Grant: In three, two, one, go!

27:27.341 --> 27:28.974
[ tires screech ]

27:28.976 --> 27:32.278
Narrator:
With both cars accelerating to 75...

27:32.280 --> 27:33.513
70 miles an hour.

27:33.515 --> 27:35.282
...Kari, again, lets go of the wheel...

27:35.284 --> 27:36.449
Hands off the wheel.

27:36.451 --> 27:38.385
...but keeps her foot on the gas.

27:38.387 --> 27:40.754
Tory:
Looks like those guys are out of control!

27:40.756 --> 27:43.191
Narrator: Tory gets in position,

27:43.193 --> 27:45.660
and then starts pumping the brakes.

27:48.131 --> 27:50.098
Hunh! Ohh!

27:50.100 --> 27:51.533
[ tires screech ]

27:51.535 --> 27:55.236
Narrator: At this speed, the cars
rapidly head off course.

27:56.905 --> 27:58.839
With the fence getting ever closer...

27:58.841 --> 28:00.674
Oh !@#*!

28:00.676 --> 28:03.977
...Tory's wheels lock up, and he veers off.

28:05.379 --> 28:08.047
Fortunately, he recovers...

28:08.049 --> 28:10.083
just in time.

28:10.085 --> 28:11.385
Grant: Ha!

28:11.387 --> 28:13.454
- That was hairball.
- Dude!

28:13.456 --> 28:16.023
I had both feet on the brakes,

28:16.025 --> 28:17.959
and I still wasn't stopping.

28:17.961 --> 28:20.094
We saw we were getting
closer and closer to the gate.

28:20.096 --> 28:21.396
I'm like, "Oh, man".

28:21.398 --> 28:23.766
I was like, "Oh, I'm gonna
push him through the fence".

28:23.768 --> 28:26.669
Narrator: Without doubt, it was
the hardest rescue yet,

28:26.671 --> 28:29.705
as Tory's smoking tires attest.

28:29.707 --> 28:32.142
But he did pull it off.

28:32.944 --> 28:35.078
What I think we learned
from this, though,

28:35.080 --> 28:39.216
is that you <i>can</i> stop a car
even going 70 miles an hour.

28:39.218 --> 28:41.885
Unless we're gonna do this whole
thing at 100 miles an hour,

28:41.887 --> 28:43.320
I think we have to call it.

28:43.322 --> 28:44.788
This one is confirmed.

28:44.790 --> 28:46.990
- Totally confirmed.
- Confirmed.

28:46.992 --> 28:48.257
[ groans ]

28:48.259 --> 28:49.559
Narrator: Confirmed it is,

28:49.561 --> 28:52.662
but not something you should try at home.

28:52.664 --> 28:54.664
[ tires screech, crash ]

28:55.866 --> 28:58.335
Now, most people would call it quits,

28:58.337 --> 29:01.004
but Kari's got an appetite for more.

29:01.006 --> 29:02.773
So, this rescue myth has reminded me

29:02.775 --> 29:05.442
of a technique I've heard of
that I've always wanted to try

29:05.444 --> 29:08.144
where you actually can
sandwich a car with two cars

29:08.146 --> 29:09.412
to slow it down.

29:09.414 --> 29:11.247
Oh, so they wedge the runaway car

29:11.249 --> 29:13.216
and use friction to bring it to a stop.

29:13.218 --> 29:14.584
A car sandwich.

29:14.586 --> 29:16.520
That sounds dangerous. I love it.

29:16.522 --> 29:19.390
Narrator: So, hungerin' for more action,

29:19.392 --> 29:23.827
Grant and Tory are about to put
the squeeze on Kari's car.

29:23.829 --> 29:25.529
Tory: So, we showed that it's possible

29:25.531 --> 29:28.866
to stop an out-of-control
car with another car,

29:28.868 --> 29:30.834
but now we're back at the Alameda runway,

29:30.836 --> 29:33.571
and this time, we're gonna try
to stop an out-of-control car

29:33.573 --> 29:35.006
with <i>two</i> cars.

29:35.008 --> 29:36.674
We're making a car sandwich.

29:36.676 --> 29:39.810
Basically, this thing we're
about to do right here...

29:39.812 --> 29:42.279
this is the most dangerous thing
we're gonna do all week.

29:42.281 --> 29:43.580
Narrator: You heard right.

29:43.582 --> 29:45.849
If they overcook this sandwich maneuver,

29:45.851 --> 29:48.586
Kari's toast.

29:48.588 --> 29:50.588
So far, I've been able to handle this,

29:50.590 --> 29:52.623
but I noticed that I put my seat belt on

29:52.625 --> 29:54.892
just a little bit tighter for this one.

29:54.894 --> 29:56.961
Grant: In three, two, one.

29:56.963 --> 29:58.996
Narrator: Most sane people would see this

29:58.998 --> 30:01.465
as a seriously crazy thing to try...

30:01.467 --> 30:03.835
Kari driving with stuck accelerator,

30:03.837 --> 30:05.903
no hands, at silly speed...

30:05.905 --> 30:07.505
and they'd be right.

30:07.507 --> 30:08.940
There's a real danger here

30:08.942 --> 30:12.745
of one, two, or all three cars rolling.

30:12.747 --> 30:16.215
Grant and Tory pull
alongside, move closer, and...

30:16.217 --> 30:18.552
[ tires screeching ]

30:19.788 --> 30:21.822
well, you can see the result.

30:21.824 --> 30:23.925
Tory: Whoo-hoo-hoo!

30:23.927 --> 30:25.659
[ Grant laughs ]

30:25.661 --> 30:26.861
Oh, my God! It worked!

30:26.863 --> 30:29.263
[ laughter ]

30:29.265 --> 30:32.600
Oh, my gosh! It worked!

30:32.602 --> 30:36.136
It was ugly, but I think it worked.

30:36.138 --> 30:38.872
Tory: We stopped an out-of-control
car with two cars.

30:38.874 --> 30:40.373
Kari: Oh, my God. It's working!

30:40.375 --> 30:42.274
Tory: I would have to say that's working.

30:42.276 --> 30:45.444
Kari: It definitely was successful
in stopping the car.

30:45.446 --> 30:47.946
But, man, I think we could do this better.

30:47.948 --> 30:50.882
I mean, this was super clumsy.

30:50.884 --> 30:53.118
[ tires screech ]

30:56.122 --> 30:58.390
Narrator:
And having survived that rescue,

30:58.392 --> 31:00.592
Kari's throwing down the gauntlet

31:00.594 --> 31:03.530
for a custom-built challenge.

31:04.332 --> 31:07.567
Why don't you guys
figure out a better way

31:07.569 --> 31:09.603
to stop the out-of-control vehicle?

31:09.605 --> 31:10.937
What if both of you go off

31:10.939 --> 31:13.273
and come up with your
own ways to stop a car,

31:13.275 --> 31:15.042
and I'll give you a challenge

31:15.044 --> 31:17.044
as a <i>really</i> out-of-control vehicle?

31:17.046 --> 31:18.846
You like being out of control, don't you?

31:18.848 --> 31:22.651
Narrator:
Next up, will Tut's tomb ever see daylight?

31:22.653 --> 31:24.153
Jamie: That is intense.

31:29.349 --> 31:31.717
Narrator: Back on Treasure Island,

31:31.719 --> 31:33.685
the San Francisco sun is finally smiling

31:33.687 --> 31:35.953
on Jamie and Adam's test setup...

31:35.955 --> 31:37.254
I'm in the door.

31:37.256 --> 31:40.357
...meaning they can finally
attempt a real-world test

31:40.359 --> 31:43.760
using their large tomb and the real sun.

31:43.762 --> 31:45.094
Jamie: Yeah, baby!

31:45.096 --> 31:47.263
The problem is, unlike
all their other tests,

31:47.265 --> 31:50.466
they can't just point
the sun straight inside.

31:50.468 --> 31:52.400
I think we're set. Should
we bring in the sun?

31:52.402 --> 31:53.801
Let's bring it in.

31:53.803 --> 31:56.470
Okay. House lights out.

31:56.472 --> 31:58.705
Instead, they have to bounce it in,

31:58.707 --> 32:01.608
courtesy of a primary mirror outside.

32:01.610 --> 32:03.210
Jamie: Wow. Look at that.

32:03.212 --> 32:05.012
I'm gonna go for the first mirror.

32:05.014 --> 32:06.213
Okay.

32:06.215 --> 32:08.048
But once that's sorted...

32:08.050 --> 32:09.750
That is intense.

32:09.752 --> 32:12.386
We got a beam in the room. Here I am.

32:12.388 --> 32:13.454
Here it comes.

32:13.456 --> 32:15.156
...it's then back to the tricky task

32:15.158 --> 32:18.059
of aligning all the mirrors...

32:18.061 --> 32:21.162
[ laughs ] Okay.

32:21.164 --> 32:22.230
That's pretty good.

32:22.232 --> 32:24.999
Look at that. It's actually working.

32:25.001 --> 32:26.401
...one by one...

32:26.403 --> 32:27.669
Going for mirror two.

32:27.671 --> 32:30.104
Oh, right. Mirror two.

32:30.106 --> 32:31.973
...until the end target is lit.

32:31.975 --> 32:33.507
Mirror three.

32:34.309 --> 32:35.276
Ohh!

32:35.278 --> 32:36.343
There we go.

32:36.345 --> 32:38.379
That's beautiful. All right.

32:38.381 --> 32:40.414
I'm gonna bring it in on our last target.

32:41.483 --> 32:44.352
And there it is.

32:44.354 --> 32:46.555
[ laughs ] Perfect.

32:46.557 --> 32:48.457
That is fantastic.

32:48.459 --> 32:50.059
This is the best yet.

32:50.061 --> 32:52.762
I can totally see things in here.

32:52.764 --> 32:54.064
But what are the lux levels?

32:54.066 --> 32:57.868
2.51 lux.

32:57.870 --> 33:00.138
That's amazing. That's really bright.

33:00.140 --> 33:01.406
They've cracked it.

33:01.408 --> 33:04.075
Six times brighter than
the minimum eye level,

33:04.077 --> 33:06.544
enough to put a smile on Adam's dial...

33:06.546 --> 33:07.946
well, briefly.

33:07.948 --> 33:10.081
Adam: - We're losing our beam.
- Yeah, we are.

33:10.083 --> 33:12.684
- You know what the problem is.
- What?

33:12.686 --> 33:14.319
The sun's moving.

33:14.321 --> 33:16.955
The relationships have all
changed a little bit, Jamie.

33:16.957 --> 33:18.757
- Have they?
- Yeah.

33:18.759 --> 33:20.860
The sun's moved off the primary,

33:20.862 --> 33:24.131
which means the aim on the
secondary is a little bit off.

33:24.133 --> 33:26.099
As the sun moves off the primary mirror,

33:26.101 --> 33:28.536
it kicks all the others out of kilter.

33:28.538 --> 33:29.837
And the sun's moved again.

33:29.839 --> 33:31.940
- I'm gonna kick the primary one more time.
- Okay.

33:31.942 --> 33:36.111
And for lighting up a
tomb, that <i>is</i> a problem.

33:36.113 --> 33:37.646
Jamie: The thing about using the sun

33:37.648 --> 33:39.915
is that the earth is rotating on its axis

33:39.917 --> 33:42.384
and it's also rotating around the sun,

33:42.386 --> 33:44.620
which means that from our perspective,

33:44.622 --> 33:47.523
the sun is moving all over
the place across the sky.

33:47.525 --> 33:49.191
So you can't really expect

33:49.193 --> 33:52.260
to be able to aim a beam
of light using a mirror

33:52.262 --> 33:53.795
at a specific spot

33:53.797 --> 33:55.564
without constantly adjusting it

33:55.566 --> 33:57.699
to accommodate for the sun's movement.

33:57.701 --> 34:00.268
Narrator:
And its movement is surprisingly fast.

34:00.270 --> 34:02.337
Adam:
With this much distance on these mirrors,

34:02.339 --> 34:04.139
the amount the sun's moving on the last one

34:04.141 --> 34:05.674
is like inches per minute.

34:05.676 --> 34:08.077
Well, it works, but only for
about three minutes at a time

34:08.079 --> 34:09.478
before the sun moves.

34:09.480 --> 34:12.415
The mirrors are static.
They don't move dynamically.

34:12.417 --> 34:16.253
But the sun does, and as the
sun moves through the sky,

34:16.255 --> 34:18.621
it changes its geometry
on the primary mirror,

34:18.623 --> 34:19.822
which changes the geometry

34:19.824 --> 34:21.623
on all the other mirrors in this room.

34:21.626 --> 34:23.059
They'd have to be moved dynamically

34:23.061 --> 34:25.127
throughout the whole thing
to keep this room lit.

34:25.129 --> 34:27.062
So, because of that, I don't feel like

34:27.063 --> 34:29.498
we've really seen the theory
behind this technique

34:29.500 --> 34:31.534
work as well as it could.

34:31.536 --> 34:34.570
Narrator: Yep, and that's something
that didn't happen in the movie.

34:34.572 --> 34:37.172
But before the sun sets on this myth,

34:37.174 --> 34:40.341
Jamie's got one little trick up his sleeve.

34:44.947 --> 34:48.081
Kari, Grant, and Tory
have confirmed the myth.

34:48.083 --> 34:51.252
You <i>can</i> stop an out-of-control
car with another

34:51.254 --> 34:54.922
with a brake-and-bumper technique...

34:54.924 --> 34:57.258
[ Tory laughs ]

34:57.260 --> 34:59.660
...plus that crazy sandwich combo.

34:59.662 --> 35:01.128
[ Grant laughs ]

35:01.130 --> 35:04.967
Now, Kari's set the boys a challenge...

35:04.969 --> 35:08.404
to come up with a custom-built
device to stop a car.

35:08.406 --> 35:09.939
Grant: Ramming speed.

35:09.941 --> 35:13.743
"Challenge". Ahh. Such a nice ring to it.

35:15.279 --> 35:18.248
So, with a mix of metal
and midnight oil later...

35:18.250 --> 35:19.282
Perfect.

35:19.284 --> 35:21.017
...they come up with a typical

35:21.019 --> 35:23.419
ingenious "MythBusters" solution.

35:23.421 --> 35:24.520
Yeah.

35:24.522 --> 35:26.956
Now they're ready to reveal all...

35:26.958 --> 35:29.358
Come on, you guys! Try and stop me!

35:29.360 --> 35:32.060
Narrator: ...Grant first.

35:32.062 --> 35:33.728
To address Kari's challenge

35:33.730 --> 35:36.297
to come up with a better way to stop a car,

35:36.299 --> 35:38.433
I have this.

35:38.435 --> 35:42.070
These paddles mount underneath
the front bumper of each car.

35:42.072 --> 35:45.106
Employing the sandwich
technique, we'll come in,

35:45.108 --> 35:48.544
and they will allow us to
control the runaway car

35:48.546 --> 35:50.947
and bring it to a safe stop.

35:50.949 --> 35:52.782
All right.

35:52.784 --> 35:56.352
See, the other car's
bumper comes in like this.

35:56.354 --> 35:59.089
We don't have to get so far in front,

35:59.091 --> 36:01.824
so there's no chance of spinning out,

36:01.826 --> 36:04.860
and we just lock you in with a "L" shape

36:04.862 --> 36:06.228
and slow you down.

36:06.230 --> 36:08.163
Sounds good on paper.

36:08.165 --> 36:12.466
Sounds bad when that's
through the grille of the car.

36:12.468 --> 36:13.834
[ chuckles ]

36:13.836 --> 36:15.636
Narrator: As for Tory's approach...

36:15.638 --> 36:18.138
All you need to do is get
your car going really fast

36:18.140 --> 36:20.540
and then rear-end the car
that's out of control.

36:20.542 --> 36:24.244
The whole idea here is that you
harpoon the car in front of you.

36:24.246 --> 36:28.216
Once you are inside the car,
you release that hook.

36:28.218 --> 36:31.720
Kari: Really? This is your idea?

36:31.722 --> 36:34.923
It might give you whiplash,
but it should stop your car.

36:34.925 --> 36:38.661
Your idea of a safe stop is to shank me?

36:38.663 --> 36:40.296
More like harpooning.

36:40.298 --> 36:43.899
Narrator: Next, custom-built-car craziness.

36:43.901 --> 36:46.401
Kari:
Nothing about it seems like a good idea.

36:51.306 --> 36:53.640
Narrator: It's crunch time at Alameda.

36:53.642 --> 36:56.476
Grant's sandwich-maker
machine is warmed up...

36:56.478 --> 36:57.678
[ engine revs ]

36:57.680 --> 36:59.012
...ready to save Kari.

36:59.014 --> 37:00.914
Kari: Ready to drive.

37:00.916 --> 37:02.649
Grant: Three, two, one, go.

37:02.651 --> 37:04.651
[ tires screech ]

37:04.653 --> 37:06.853
Narrator: Grant's ingeniously bolted bars

37:06.855 --> 37:08.254
to the front of each car...

37:08.256 --> 37:10.356
Kari: 40.

37:10.358 --> 37:12.091
50. Here they come.

37:12.093 --> 37:16.129
Narrator: ...to act like a barrier
to stop Kari's car.

37:16.131 --> 37:17.931
Now, it may look crazy...

37:17.933 --> 37:18.965
Kari: Whoa!

37:21.770 --> 37:23.837
[ tires screech ]
[ Grant laughs ]

37:23.839 --> 37:25.506
...but it's blitzed the job.

37:28.678 --> 37:30.412
Grant: - Whoo!
Tory: - Gotcha.

37:30.414 --> 37:32.481
Whoo!

37:32.483 --> 37:34.584
Gotcha!

37:34.586 --> 37:35.952
That was beautiful!

37:35.954 --> 37:38.388
That worked so much better
than the original sandwich.

37:38.390 --> 37:41.691
Oh, my God. We totally got you.

37:41.693 --> 37:43.426
That was awesome.

37:43.428 --> 37:45.562
Grant, your method is safer.

37:45.564 --> 37:47.230
- Nice work.
- Thank you. Thanks.

37:47.232 --> 37:49.700
Now if we can only get the cars apart.

37:49.702 --> 37:52.003
Are we gonna have to
drive them home like this?

37:52.305 --> 37:55.840
I get to a constant speed,
take my hands off the wheel,

37:55.842 --> 37:59.143
and watch the cars on either side of me

37:59.145 --> 38:02.113
start to close in very, very quickly.

38:02.115 --> 38:05.684
They slam at the same time.

38:05.686 --> 38:07.653
My bumper hits the front paddles,

38:07.655 --> 38:11.124
and they actually are slowing me down.

38:11.126 --> 38:14.927
I smell rubber burning,
but I'm coming to a stop.

38:14.929 --> 38:17.029
It's amazing.

38:17.431 --> 38:19.197
Narrator:
And if that wasn't scary enough,

38:19.199 --> 38:21.166
then there's the harpoon.

38:22.367 --> 38:23.867
This is a new technique.

38:23.869 --> 38:26.603
This is more of a stabbing, hooking,

38:26.605 --> 38:28.939
and then using the weight of the vehicle

38:28.941 --> 38:31.574
to slow the out-of-control car down.

38:31.576 --> 38:35.077
This plan... nothing about
it seems like a good idea.

38:35.079 --> 38:39.582
Harpooning the back of my car,
ramming it as hard as you can...

38:39.584 --> 38:41.684
who comes up with this kind of idea?

38:41.686 --> 38:44.421
Only a crazy person.

38:44.423 --> 38:46.890
I think we're set.

38:46.892 --> 38:49.894
Narrator: It's a simple plan...
get up behind Kari's car,

38:49.896 --> 38:53.131
crash into the trunk, slam on your brakes.

38:53.133 --> 38:55.200
What could possibly go wrong?

38:55.202 --> 38:57.836
Tory: Three, two, one, go.

39:01.776 --> 39:03.076
Yeah!

39:03.078 --> 39:06.247
The runway road warrior
sets out, ready to rescue.

39:06.249 --> 39:10.819
Grant: This is Tory and Grant in
harpoon rescue, in pursuit.

39:10.821 --> 39:13.321
Okay, hands off the wheel. Go for it, man!

39:14.890 --> 39:16.791
Here we go!

39:21.296 --> 39:23.531
Narrator: Kari's car is skewered.

39:23.533 --> 39:26.433
Now, on the sophistication
scale, it's crafty.

39:26.435 --> 39:29.937
As for the all-important
results rating, it's a hit.

