41:04.440 --> 41:06.874
In their earlier small-scale tests,

41:06.876 --> 41:10.277
Jamie made an ambient-light
level breakthrough.

41:10.279 --> 41:11.512
Jamie: The goal of all this

41:11.514 --> 41:13.881
is to raise the ambient-light
level in a room,

41:13.883 --> 41:16.651
and mirrors alone aren't gonna cut it.

41:16.653 --> 41:19.153
That light needs to hit
something that scatters it.

41:19.155 --> 41:22.423
Narrator:
So now, in their full-size, sunlit tomb,

41:22.425 --> 41:26.660
he's itching to see if this
scatter theory will scale.

41:26.662 --> 41:28.462
Turn off your head lamp and check this out.

41:31.065 --> 41:34.467
[ laughs ] That's beautiful!

41:34.469 --> 41:36.502
And you thought I didn't know
how to light up a room.

41:36.504 --> 41:39.338
I stand corrected. Let's take a reading.

41:39.940 --> 41:41.674
Okay.

41:41.676 --> 41:44.110
Maximum.

41:45.312 --> 41:47.545
All right. Moving away.

41:47.547 --> 41:51.348
Average lux... 8.62 lux!

41:51.350 --> 41:53.884
Whoo for Jamie's shirt.

41:53.886 --> 41:56.987
Amazingly, with this reflective scattering,

41:56.989 --> 41:58.522
Jamie's whiter-than-white shirt

41:58.524 --> 42:00.791
has given the maximum light reading

42:00.793 --> 42:02.292
for the entire experiment.

42:02.294 --> 42:04.127
Adam's gobsmacked.

42:04.129 --> 42:06.330
Adam: Well, it turns out that
Jamie's starched white shirt

42:06.332 --> 42:10.502
provides almost three times as
much ambient light in this space

42:10.504 --> 42:14.740
as the next best technique
of everything that we've tried.

42:14.742 --> 42:18.411
Narrator:
And Jamie's reaction? Well, this <i>is</i> Jamie.

42:18.413 --> 42:20.313
Jamie: A mirrored surface is
gonna be your best bet

42:20.315 --> 42:23.216
to get light into a room
because it's very directional.

42:23.218 --> 42:25.486
But if you want to actually light the room

42:25.488 --> 42:27.054
once that light gets in there,

42:27.056 --> 42:29.657
you're best off if it hits
a surface like my white shirt

42:29.659 --> 42:32.561
because the white isn't so directional.

42:32.563 --> 42:35.531
It's gonna spread the light and
raise your ambient-light level.

42:35.533 --> 42:38.334
How do you want to wrap this up?

42:38.936 --> 42:40.969
In theory, it's plausible,

42:40.971 --> 42:42.737
because the sun's rays did, in fact,

42:42.739 --> 42:45.306
provide enough ambient light
to move around in the room.

42:45.308 --> 42:47.742
I agree. Plausible.

42:47.744 --> 42:49.811
But totally impractical.

42:49.813 --> 42:52.514
First of all, the sun moves,
so you only get that light

42:52.516 --> 42:53.715
for about 3 1/2 minutes

42:53.717 --> 42:55.050
before you have to shift everything.

42:55.052 --> 42:56.952
And the idea that all those mirrors

42:56.954 --> 42:58.720
would sit around for 3,000 years

42:58.722 --> 43:00.689
and be ready to light up that room...

43:00.691 --> 43:02.057
totally ridiculous.

